Highlight figures¶

Figure 1¶

Figure 1 maps the number of Airbnb Listings and the median Airbnb listing price on the Greater Boston Area (Boston and Cambridge) map. We can see in the first subfigure that places that are far away from downtown are more likely to have more listings. However, from the second subfigure, we see that places near downtown can have very high median listing price.

Figure 2¶

Figure 2 analyzes the number of listings, median price of listings and median review per month of listings of neighourhood against the black/african american population of that neighbourhood. We can observe that with the increasing of the black/african american population in a neighbourhood, the average price of listings goes down, though the number of listing and average reviews per month not neccessarily goes down. Additionally, the area with the most black/african american population has the most number of listings, however the average price is only about 75\$ where neighbourhoods with less black/african american population can have the average listing prices up to 225\$.

def knn_binning(x_values, y_values, num_bins = 40, logged = True):
    max_degree = max(x_values)
    min_degree = min(x_values)
    
    if logged:
        lower_bound = np.log10(min_degree) if min_degree >= 0.001 else 0.0
        upper_bound = np.log10(max_degree+0.001)
        bins = np.logspace(lower_bound,upper_bound,num_bins, base=10)   
    else:
        bins = np.linspace(min_degree,max_degree+0.001,num_bins)   
            
    start = bins[:-1]
    end = bins[1:]
    center = start + (end-start)*0.5
    

    knn_k = dict((k,0.0) for k in range(len(center)))
    counts = dict((k,0.0) for k in range(len(center)))

    for i in range(len(x_values)):
        x = x_values[i]
        index = np.argmax((x>=start) & (x<end))
        c = center[index]
        knn_k[index] += y_values[i]
        counts[index] += 1
    
    x = []
    y = []
    for k,v in list(counts.items()):
        if v != 0:
            y.append(knn_k[k]/counts[k])
            x.append(center[k])    
            
    return x,y

def get_max_rows(df):
    srape_later = df.groupby('id').last_scraped.transform(max)
    return df[df.last_scraped == srape_later]

Important Charateristics to Attract Reservations¶

It is pretty important to know what characteristics will attract more reservations. Since we don't have exact reservation data, we use number of reviews as a proxy to evaluate the hotness of the place.

In [506]:
# Filter out the listings that lack reviews per month information
listing_great_boston_review_filter = listing_great_boston.dropna(subset = ["reviews_per_month"])

We see that the range of review per month is not very high, comparing different regions, East Boston, North End and Wellington-Harrington has the highest average review per month, Fenway, Straberry Hill and West end has the lowest average, but we notice that there are a lot of "outliers" for each area. Therefore, neighbourhood is probably not a good indicator of hotness.

The expericeny of a host might influence the hotness of their listings as well. When we investigate the host listing count agains the review per month, we see that there is a slightly increasing and then decreasing as the listing count increases. This is maybe due to that when the host has more listings, but not too many, they have more energy to devote in it and might get more reviews; but when they have too many listings, they might be too busy to take care of all the listings so the number of reviews goes down.

Availability analysis¶

Besides looking at the reviews, availability can be a proxy to show the hotness as well. Though not a perfect proxy because a listing coule be unavailable due to other reasons other than booked.

Avalability days with neighbourhood¶

In [514]:
plt.figure(figsize = (20, 10))
order = listing_great_boston.groupby("neighbourhood")["availability_365"].median().fillna(0).sort_values()[::-1].index
sns.violinplot(x = "neighbourhood", y = "availability_365", data = listing_great_boston, order = order, cut = 0)
plt.xticks(rotation = 90);

From the violinplot we can see that for most neighbourhood, the distribution is kind of bimodal, one mode on the lower end and one mode on the higher end. We see that on average, listing Roslindale has the highest available days, indicating the reservation rate is probably not that high and Allston has the lowest available days.

Airbnb, Geospatial, and Analyze Boston Data¶

With neighbourhood data, Airbnb data is naturally geospatial, therefore it will be good to visualize them on a map. Additionally, Airbnb data can also show some underlying patterns about the cities, and together with Analyze Boston data, we might be able to discover some interesting phenomena.

Load Analyze Boston data and merge with Airbnb data¶

neighbourhood = listing_great_boston.groupby("neighbourhood")
neighbourhood_list_count = neighbourhood.count()
neighbourhood_list_avg_price = neighbourhood.price.median()
neighbourhood_review_per_month = neighbourhood.reviews_per_month.median()
neighbourhood_availability = neighbourhood.availability_365.median()
temp_df = pd.DataFrame()
temp_df['neighbourhood'] = neighbourhood_list_count.index
temp_df['count'] = list(neighbourhood_list_count["id"])
temp_df['avg_price'] = list(neighbourhood_list_avg_price)
temp_df['avg_review_per_month'] = list(neighbourhood_review_per_month)
temp_df['availability'] = list(neighbourhood_availability)
merged = great_boston.set_index('neighbourhood').join(temp_df.set_index('neighbourhood')).join(race_recent.set_index("Neighborhood")).join(housing_recent.set_index("Neighborhood"), lsuffix='_race', rsuffix='_housing').join(population_df.set_index("Neighborhood"))
